	interface Props {
		sdgColor?: string;
	}

	let { sdgColor = getSdgColor(15) }: Props = $props();
</script>

<div class="lesson-content">

	<MaterialsList materials={[{"name":"A variety of natural items (leaves, twigs, flowers, seeds, pinecones, stones, bark, etc.)","isOptional":false},{"name":"Can be both collected by students and in classroom for student use. Encourage students to collect responsibly and ethically, avoiding damage to living plants or habitats.","isOptional":false},{"name":"Glue","isOptional":false},{"name":"String or twine","isOptional":false},{"name":"Paper or cardboard","isOptional":false},{"name":"Images or videos of diverse terrestrial ecosystems (forests, grasslands, westlands, etc.), threatened species, deforestation and land degradation, etc.","isOptional":false},{"name":"Examples of land art or environmental art examples","isOptional":false},{"name":"Whiteboard or large chart paper","isOptional":false},{"name":"Markers","isOptional":false},{"name":"Notebooks or paper","isOptional":false},{"name":"Pens/Pencils","isOptional":false}]} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"(30-60 MINUTES)"} content={"<strong>Introduction</strong><br>Begin with a clear and engaging introduction or reintroduction of UN Global Goal 15: Protect, restore, and promote sustainable use of terrestrial ecosystems, sustainably manage forests, combat desertification, and half and reverse land degradation and half biodiversity loss. Emphasize the importance of terrestrial ecosystems for life on Earth.<br>Facilitate a class discussion:\n<ul>\n<li>What are your favorite natural places on land?</li>\n<li>What are some of the biggest threats to these places?</li>\n<li>How can art help us appreciate and protect nature?</li>\n</ul><br>Explain the concept of natural art or land art.\n<ul>\n<li>Natural art uses natural materials to create art in or about the natural world.</li>\n<li>It can be temporary or permanent, large-scale or small-scale.</li>\n<li>It often emphasizes the beauty and fragility of nature.</li>\n</ul><br>Show examples of land art:\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.google.com/search?q=Andy+Goldsworthy+art&amp;sca_esv=9c491feca8eb3a39&amp;rlz=1C5CHFA_enUS1124US1124&amp;udm=2&amp;biw=1198&amp;bih=727&amp;sxsrf=AHTn8zrAgNbk0c89RNdyqaBsAXK03Hn_4Q%3A1744752320993&amp;ei=wM7-Z7ylPLWKwN4Pw--t4QY&amp;ved=0ahUKEwi8hcHy_NqMAxU1BdAFHcN3K2wQ4dUDCBE&amp;uact=5&amp;oq=Andy+Goldsworthy+art&amp;gs_lp=EgNpbWciFEFuZHkgR29sZsworthy+artMgUQABiABDIFEAAYgAQyChAAGIAEGEMYigUyBRAAGIAEMgUQABiABDIFEAAYgAQyBRAAGIAEMgUQABiABDIFEAAYgAQyBRAAGIAESJEGUK8CWOUEcAF4AJABAJgBN6AByQGqAQE0uAEDyAEA-AEBmAIFoALrAcICEBAAGIAEGLEDGEMYgwEYigXCAgYQABgHGB6YAwCIBgGSBwE1oAfxFrIHATS4B-AB&amp;sclient=img\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Andy Goldsworthy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.google.com/search?sca_esv=aca16de1709f852f&amp;rlz=1C5CHFA_enUS1124US1124&amp;sxsrf=AHTn8zo_CqL6ytVQJg-chBOobTDJo6zcSg:1744752362705&amp;q=Robert+Smithson+art&amp;udm=2&amp;fbs=ABzOT_CWdhQLP1FcmU5B0fn3xuWpA-dk4wpBWOGsoR7DG5zJBsxayPSIAqObp_AgjkUGqensJR8Rz2PphQzhi4JPzwOL41jAKImdqfcm5f6z1FIS-IgTGlRGj70JJPKHKqb7lExQKtTIYvJQ0hJ9yNZYK6kiBTVaVtnIgI3YVklhBgdFSqhe2wXgIm39z9OFwAdUaHy-V_DOGi0q8tN3j4UtjdG6cqwzsQ&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=2ahUKEwji_LKG_dqMAxU9wskDHYN1LNIQtKgLegQIHxAB&amp;biw=1198&amp;bih=727&amp;dpr=2\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Robert Smithson</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.google.com/search?sca_esv=7fc613d9cd9ef286&amp;rlz=1C5CHFA_enUS1124US1124&amp;udm=2&amp;fbs=AIIjpHxU7SXXniUZfeShr2fp4giZ1Y6MJ25_tmWITc7uy4KIeioyp3OhN11EY0n5qfq-zEMZldv_eRjZ2XLYc5GnVnMEIxC4WQfoNDH7FwchyAayyomVtyMIlwCjX48LT0TrXSNU5mLhW4DIlZIt3-gwG8mMeXC-Y0JFzx5GBuU59za0o5XLXRovSVas40d3y4gTUxobLZ8-C-h3aNfCXmcENPvCZqzMdA&amp;q=Agnes+Denes+land+art&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=2ahUKEwiLgaqR_7qPAxUR5ckDHYHVLDEQtKgLegQIFRAB&amp;biw=1327&amp;bih=671&amp;dpr=2\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Agnes Denes</a></li>\n</ul><br>Discuss the potential of natural art to:\n<ul>\n<li>Connect people to nature.</li>\n<li>Raise awareness about environmental issues.</li>\n<li>Promote sustainable practices.</li>\n</ul>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Natural Item Exploration and Concept Development"} content={"<p>Students share the natural items they collected, describing where they found them and why they were drawn to them.\\<br>AND/OR<br>Students share the natural items they chose from the options available in the classroom, and speaking about why they were drawn to them.<br>Discuss the diversity of colors, textures, shapes, and sizes.<br>Facilitate a class brainstorming session to generate ideas for natural art projects inspired by Global Goal 15.<br>Provide examples and prompts connected to different targets, as well as the Goal as a whole.\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Global Goal 15</strong> <em>(As a whole)</em></li>\n<li>Create an artwork that represents the interconnectedness of all living things.</li>\n<li>Create an artwork that shows two contrasting visuals: one showing a healthy ecosystem, the other a degraded one.</li>\n<li>Create an artwork that represents the natural cycle of life, death, and renewal.</li>\n<li>Create an artwork that explores the relationship between humans and terrestrial ecosystems.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 15.1</strong> <em>(Conservation of Ecosystems)</em></li>\n<li>Create a miniature forest scene using leaves, twigs, and moss.</li>\n<li>Arrange natural items to represent a wetland or river system.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 15.2</strong> <em>(Sustainable Forest Management)</em></li>\n<li>Use twigs or bark to create a small sculpture that symbolizes the importance of trees.</li>\n<li>Create patterns or mosaics with different types of leaves.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 15.3</strong> <em>(Combating Desertification)</em></li>\n<li>Use dry materials like sand, stones, and dried grasses to depict a desert landscape.</li>\n<li>Create a contrasting piece that shows the restoration of degraded land.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 15.4</strong> <em>(Conservation of Mountain Ecosystems)</em></li>\n<li>Use stones, twigs, and leaves to build a miniature mountain range.</li>\n<li>Create a piece that shows the different vegetation zones of a mountain.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 15.5</strong> <em>(Reducing Degradation and Biodiversity Loss)</em></li>\n<li>Arrange natural items to represent endangered species.</li>\n<li>Create a piece that shows the impact of habitat destruction.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 15.6</strong> <em>(Fair Sharing of Genetic Resources)</em></li>\n<li>Create a piece that symbolizes the interconnectedness of different plant species.</li>\n<li>Use natural items from different places to represent global collaboration.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 15.7</strong> <em>(Ending Poaching and Trafficking)</em></li>\n<li>Use natural items to create a symbolic representation of an animal threatened by poaching.</li>\n<li>Create a piece that depicts the beauty and value of wildlife.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 15.8</strong> <em>(Invasive Alien Species)</em></li>\n<li>Create a piece that shows the disruption caused by invasive species to a native ecosystem.</li>\n<li>Use contrasting materials to represent native vs. invasive species.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 15.9</strong> <em>(Integrating Ecosystem Values)</em></li>\n<li>Create a piece that shows the benefits that ecosystems provide to humans.</li>\n<li>Use natural items to represent different ecosystem services (e.g., clean water, pollination).</li>\n<li><strong>Target 15.a</strong> <em>(Mobilizing Financial Resources)</em></li>\n<li>Use natural items to create a piece that represents the flow of money towards conservation efforts.</li>\n<li>Use different colors or textures to symbolize different sources of funding.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 15.b</strong> <em>(Financing Sustainble Forest Management)</em></li>\n<li>Create a piece that shows the economic and environmental benefits of sustainable forestry.</li>\n<li>Use different types of wood or bark to represent sustainable vs. unsustainable practices.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 15.c</strong> <em>(Combating Poaching and Trafficking)</em></li>\n<li>Create a piece that empowers local communities to protect wildlife and pursue sustainable livelihoods.</li>\n<li>Use natural items to represent the connection between people and nature.</li>\n</ul><br>Encourage students to:\n<ul>\n<li>Choose a target or aspect of Global Goal 15 that resonates with them.</li>\n<li>Consider the materials they have available.</li>\n<li>Think about the message they want to convey.</li>\n<li>Explore different arrangements and compositions.</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Natural Art Creation"} content={"<p>Students create their natural art pieces using their items.<br>Provide guidance and support where needed:\n<ul>\n<li>Offer tips on arranging and connecting the materials.</li>\n<li>Encourage experimentation and creativity.</li>\n<li>Help students refine their compositions and messages.</li>\n</ul><br>Emphasize that the focus is on expressing ideas and emotions, not achieving perfect realism.</p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Presentation and Discussion"} content={"<p>Students present their completed artworks to the class.<br>Facilitate a discussion during or after each presentation. Ask guiding questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>What is the main message of the artwork?</li>\n<li>How did the artist use natural materials to convey their message?</li>\n<li>How does the artwork relate to Global Goal 15 and its targets?</li>\n<li>What impact do you think the artwork could have on its viewers?</li>\n<li>What did you learn about the importance of terrestrial ecosystems through creating this art?</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Reflection and Summary"} content={"<p>Have students reflect on their learning experience through discussion or writing.<br>Ask guiding questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>How did creating art using natural items (leaves, sticks, stones, etc.) help you connect with the themes of Life on Land in a different way than using traditional art supplies?</li>\n<li>What did you learn about the beauty fragility, and interconnectedness of terrestrial ecosystems by working directly with materials from nature?</li>\n<li>Did the act of collecting (if applicable) and arranging natural items change your perspective on their value or role in the environment?</li>\n<li>What did you discover about your own creativity when limited to using only natural materials?</li>\n<li>How can art made from natural elements help us to appreciate and respect the environment around us?</li>\n<li>What new insights did you gain about Global Goal 15 and the importance of protecting, restoring, and sustainably using terrestrial ecosystems through this art exploration?</li>\n<li>How did your artwork, and those created by your classmates, highlight the diverse challenges or hopeful solutions related to specific concepts of Global Goal 15 (e.g., deforestation, biodiversity loss, combating desertification)?</li>\n<li>Did creating art about life on land make you think differently about human impact on natural habitats?</li>\n<li>What common themes or powerful messages about natures resilience or the needs for conservation emerged across the different artworks you saw?</li>\n<li>How does a hands-on artistic exploration help to make a global goal like 15 more tangible and relatable?</li>\n<li>Did creating your natural artwork spark any personal connections or reflections on your own experiences with nature or local ecosystems?</li>\n<li>What emotions did you connect with during this art activity, and how might those emotions motivate you to take action related to Global Goal 15?</li>\n<li>What is one key takeaway about life on land and the power of creative expression that you will remember from this lesson?</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Assessment"} content={"<ul>\n<li>Consistent and enthusiastic involvement in all phases of the lesson, including the initial brainstorming, natural item exploration, individual art creation, and class discussions.</li>\n<li>Comprehension of Global Goal 15, targets and core concepts. This will be evidenced through the symbolism and intention within the natural art piece and verbal explanations during sharing and discussion.</li>\n<li>Originality and effectiveness in using collected natural items to convey the message about terrestrial ecosystems, deforestation, biodiversity loss, or conservation. Look for innovative and thoughtful arrangements.</li>\n<li>How clearly and powerfully the finished artwork communicates its intended message about Global Goal 15. Did the art successfully evoke thought or emotion related to life on land?</li>\n<li>Willingness to experiment with the natural materials and techniques, embracing the unique qualities, and demonstrating problem-solving during the creative process.</li>\n<li>Ability to articulate artistic choices and to interpret and provide thoughtful feedback on classmates’ artwork, connecting it to Global Goal 15 themes.</li>\n<li>Nuance and depth of understanding demonstrated in reflections, particularly concerning the role of art in advocating for environmental change and the complexities of conserving life on land.</li>\n</ul>"} {sdgColor} />

