sruption caused by invasive species to a native ecosystem.</li>\n<li>Use contrasting materials to represent native vs. invasive species.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 15.9</strong> <em>(Integrating Ecosystem Values)</em></li>\n<li>Create a piece that shows the benefits that ecosystems provide to humans.</li>\n<li>Use natural items to represent different ecosystem services (e.g., clean water, pollination).</li>\n<li><strong>Target 15.a</strong> <em>(Mobilizing Financial Resources)</em></li>\n<li>Use natural items to create a piece that represents the flow of money towards conservation efforts.</li>\n<li>Use different colors or textures to symbolize different sources of funding.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 15.b</strong> <em>(Financing Sustainble Forest Management)</em></li>\n<li>Create a piece that shows the economic and environmental benefits of sustainable forestry.</li>\n<li>Use different types of wood or bark to represent sustainable vs. unsustainable practices.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 15.c</strong> <em>(Combating Poaching and Trafficking)</em></li>\n<li>Create a piece that empowers local communities to protect wildlife and pursue sustainable livelihoods.</li>\n<li>Use natural items to represent the connection between people and nature.</li>\n</ul><br>Encourage students to:\n<ul>\n<li>Choose a target or aspect of Global Goal 15 that resonates with them.</li>\n<li>Consider the materials they have available.</li>\n<li>Think about the message they want to convey.</li>\n<li>Explore different arrangements and compositions.</li>\n</ul><br><strong>Natural Art Creation</strong><br>Students create their natural art pieces using their items.<br>Provide guidance and support where needed:\n<ul>\n<li>Offer tips on arranging and connecting the materials.</li>\n<li>Encourage experimentation and creativity.</li>\n<li>Help students refine their compositions and messages.</li>\n</ul><br>Emphasize that the focus is on expressing ideas and emotions, not achieving perfect realism.<br><strong